<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: LINDA AND DELTA IN D.C. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 As I sat minding my own business, the phone rang and two of my favorites in 
the world were together on the other end. When I say "together," I mean 
together -- the genius TV creator Linda Bloodworth-Thomason and Delta Burke, 
the delicious "Designing Women" star. As I reported some months ago, these two 
have made up their professional differences -- and now they will finally join 
forces again with a brand-new series called "Woman in the House." 
</P>
<P>
 The pilot script is already at CBS, and they expect a green light to film the 
first episode. The series is set in Washington, but will be filmed in Little 
Rock, which is the only U.S. city that has a duplicate of D.C.'s Capitol 
Building. 
</P>
<P>
 The pilot concerns an elderly U.S. congressman from Georgia wed to a young, 
sexy woman named Lee Ann Wannamaker. He dies and she is appointed to fill out 
his term. She takes his seat but refuses to "know her place." She plunges into 
her new job with no realization that telling the truth in politics is 
dangerous. She has an adopted Asian daughter, as well as a mentally retarded 
brother. She insists on taking him everywhere in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
 When she puts her brother's ceramics on sale in the House Gift Shop, a scandal 
ensues, called "Knickknackgate." Lee Ann goes on "Crossfire" and says all the 
politically incorrect things. 
</P>
<P>
 What you must remember in considering all the above is that the accidental 
congresswoman in the series is actually Suzanne Sugarbaker, the wonderfully 
self-absorbed Southern belle of "Designing Women." For the moment, Linda is 
calling the character Lee Ann. But believe me, Lee Ann by any name is Suzanne 
all over again.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Jeff Daniels co-stars with Jim ("Ace Ventura") Carrey in New Line's "Dumb and 
Dumber." Daniels and Carrey play the world's most stupid guys in this slapstick 
comedy filming in Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
 Jeff, who made such a big, serious impression last year in "Gettysburg," will 
also be seen this summer in Fox's action pic "Speed" -- with a short-haired 
pumped-up Keanu Reeves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
