<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; TEXAS; NEW YOUTH CURFEW BEGINS IN DALLAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Police in Dallas have started enforcing a controversial curfew that requires 
youths under 17 to be at home or with chaperons after midnight on weekends and 
11 p.m. on weeknights.Because of an American Civil Liberties Union lawsuit, the 
city did not enforce the law after it passed in 1991. U.S. District Judge Jerry 
Buchmeyer ruled the law unconstitutional, but the U.S. 5th Circuit Court of 
Appeals overturned that decision. The U.S. Supreme Court has not said if it 
will hear the case. Police have said they are not going to enforce the 
ordinance aggressively. Violators can be given a warning, a ride home or a $500 
fine, or be taken into custody. 
</P>
